mkdir => directory creation
touch => file creation
-p    => file existence (creates path)
cp    => copy
--------------------------------------------

cd  => change directory
ls  => list of files
la  => complete file information
pwd => current directory
..  => previous directory
../ => back two or more directories
.   => in this directory
|   => A pipe is a form of redirection (transfer of standard output to some other destination)
       that is used to send the output of one command/program/process to another
       command/program/process for further processing.
Example: history | tail => show the last 10 lines from history

green color of the file means that the file is binary, it can be execute (.exe)

---------------------------------------------

mv       => move file
rm       => remove a file
sudo     => raise the access level to superuser
rm -r    => recursively delete all files from all folders
chmod +x => add file execution
cat      => read file history
---------------------------------------------

>         => write (create) file
>>        => modify existing file
date      => display the system date and time
tail      => shows the last 10 lines by default
tail -n   => shows the last n number of lines
head      => shows the first 10 lines by default
head -n   => shows the first n number of lines
----------------------------------------------

wc    => stands for word count
wc -l => number of lines
wc -c => number of bytes
wc -w => number of words
wc -L => can be used to print out the length of longest (number of characters) line in a file
echo  => outputs text
----------------------------------------------

history > /tmp/history.txt => redirect data and create file

vi => text editor where { i => input mode
                       exit => exit mode from input mode
           :x   :wq   :zz   => three options for exiting the editor

nano => new text editor
----------------------------------------------

top     => shows how much memory is free and how much is occupied
free -m => shows how many free megabytes of memory
Ctrl C  => is used to kill a process with signal SIGINT , in other words it is a polite kill
Ctrl Z  => is used to suspend a process by sending it the signal SIGTSTP
          , which is like a sleep signal, that can be undone and the process can be resumed again.

/proc/cpuinfo => The file /proc/cpuinfo displays what type of processor your system is running
                     including the number of CPUs presen
df -h => disk fullness

cat/etc/os-release and /usr/lib/os-release => files contain operating system identification data
-----------------------------------------------

ps    => command is used to list the currently running processes
        and their PIDs along with some other information depends on different options
grep  => command can be used to find or search a regular expression or a string in a text file
chmod => command is used to change the access mode of a file
------------------------------------------------

Reference   Class     Description
u          owner      file's owner

g          group      users who are members of
                      the file's group

o          others     users who are neither the
                      file's owner nor members of
                      the file's group

a          all       All three of the above, same as ugo
--------------------------------------------------

r       Permission to read the file.
w       Permission to write (or delete) the file.
x       Permission to execute the file, or, in
        the case of a directory, search it.
--------------------------------------------------

chown => to change the owner of file system files
         , directories. Unprivileged (regular) users who
         wish to change the group membership of a file that they own may use chgrp.
ssh  => It is a protocol used to securely connect to a remote server/system
         . ssh is secure in the sense that it transfers the data in encrypted form between
         the host and the client
pem  => Resolution. Privacy Enhanced Mail (PEM) files are concatenated certificate containers
        frequently used in certificate installations when multiple certificates that
        form a complete chain are being imported as a single file.
---------------------------------------------------

locate     => used to find the files by name
              . There is two most widely used file searching utilities accessible
              to users are called find and locate
cron       => is a clock daemon, whose name originates from Chronos
              , the Greek word for time. It enables users to automate the execution of commands
              , scripts (a group of commands) or programs at specified time intervals.

crontab => is a list of commands that you want to run on a regular schedule
           , and also the name of the command used to manage that list.
	  -e	(edit user's crontab)
	  -l	(list user's crontab)
	  -r	(delete user's crontab)
	  -i	(prompt before deleting user's crontab)
      -s	(selinux context)
-----------------------------------------------------

kill     => is a built-in command which is used to terminate processes manually.
kill -9  => unconditional interrupt
kill all => interrupt all
awk      => display a column
grep -v  => display everything except ...
grep -w  => output a line with a specific word
tr -d    => trim character
-----------------------------------------------------
                       Github

mkdir victoria_raitses => create a directory with the name of the repository
create file README.md
echo "# victoria_git" >> README.md
Set your username: git config --global user.name "FIRST_NAME LAST_NAME"
Set your email address: git config --global user.email "MY_NAME@example.com"
git init => connecting to the repository

git status    => displays the state of the working directory and the staging area
                 . It lets you see which changes have been staged, which haven't
                 , and which files aren't being tracked by Git.
git commit -m => save current state with message
git log       => view history
git remote add origin + repository link => combine local git and remote
git push -u origin master => send data from local git to remote

git branch => A branch in Git is simply a lightweight movable pointer to one of these commits.
              ... As you start making commits, you're given a master branch that points to the last commit you made
              . Every time you commit, the master branch pointer moves forward automatically
              . Note. The “master” branch in Git is not a special branch.

git checkout -b "new-branch" => creating a new branch
rm -r => delete file (repository)
explorer . => find the storage location of the local repository

